WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.160
So yeah, I'm here to talk to you about a package called parsnip that's been quite a long time

00:00:13.160 --> 00:00:14.160
in the making.

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:18.320
Before I get started, why is this called parsnip?

00:00:18.320 --> 00:00:23.520
So I have this other package called caret, C-A-R-E-T.

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:28.520
And I was joking with some people in my group that the first RStudio package I should make

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:33.080
when I joined the company should be caret, like the vegetable.

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:37.080
So then people would be like, I have a problem with caret, and I'd be like, well, is it caret?

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:38.439
Or is it caret?

00:00:38.439 --> 00:00:43.860
And then somebody, it might have been Hallie, was like, oh, parsnips are white caret.

00:00:43.860 --> 00:00:49.000
So we kind of felt like that's a good code name for the project, and then we just kept

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.200
calling it parsnip.

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:55.119
So it's parsnip.

00:00:55.119 --> 00:01:00.320
So Alex stole one of my slides.

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:01.320
That's cool.

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:07.239
But I've been kind of talking about this forever.

00:01:07.239 --> 00:01:12.680
What for me, at least, is frustrating with R packages for modeling, and it's almost always

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:15.919
it's never like the numerics, usually.

00:01:15.919 --> 00:01:18.800
It's about the user interface, right?

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:24.279
And the problem that Alex talked about is that struggle is real, in that you start using

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:27.760
an R package, or you see an R package, you're like, oh, I really want to try that out, and

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:30.559
then when you start using it, you're like, oh, no.

00:01:30.559 --> 00:01:36.080
And so sometimes people inadvertently, maybe because they don't know anything about R,

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:37.879
make the package very difficult to use.

00:01:37.879 --> 00:01:41.080
So for example, I was looking at one the other day, which I tweeted about and got really

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:47.320
angry about, expected your predictor data not to come in as a data frame, but as a matrix,

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:51.919
and that by itself is not a deal breaker, but instead of having factors or dummy variables

00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:57.680
for your qualitative predictors, they wanted to convert it to zero-based integers, right?

00:01:57.680 --> 00:02:00.120
So that's the most un-R way of doing things.

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:03.199
And so I was like, no, I'm not going to do that.

00:02:03.199 --> 00:02:08.320
But there's a lot of we do have some sort of loose conventions in R about what your

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:11.800
modeling package should look like, but you don't have to follow them, and they're not,

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:13.440
to be honest with you, all that specific.

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:19.639
So as another example, we usually have the formula method for models, and then we have

00:02:19.759 --> 00:02:24.960
the non-formula method, where you use X and Y as your arguments.

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:29.360
And so you can never really know when you start using a new package whether you have

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:31.880
either of those or both, right?

00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:34.279
So that can be kind of frustrating.

00:02:34.279 --> 00:02:38.119
One really, really frustrating thing is sometimes you get a prediction back, and I love the

00:02:38.119 --> 00:02:42.080
ranger package, but the predictions that you get out of the predict method aren't actually

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:43.080
data frames.

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:47.479
They're like a specialized ranger object, which then you have to extract the piece out

00:02:47.479 --> 00:02:49.320
that you actually want.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.039
And then I'll talk about Glimnet a little bit more, but that's another good example

00:02:52.039 --> 00:02:58.440
where if you're fitting classification models, you could get, for a prediction, you can get

00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:03.520
a vector, a matrix, or a multidimensional array back, depending on the data.

00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:06.600
And that's very frustrating to program with.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:11.160
So the point is that if you're going from model to model and trying different things,

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:13.520
you could get really frustrated.

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:19.240
And then here's the same thing that Alex showed, where just the variation in type equal

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:22.960
is substantial.

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:23.960
So we want to solve that.

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:28.039
We want to, you know, I don't want to have to worry about remembering all this stuff

00:03:28.039 --> 00:03:30.679
for all the special cases when I go to do modeling.

00:03:30.679 --> 00:03:35.139
And so I tried solving that, or I did kind of solve that with caret previously.

00:03:35.139 --> 00:03:41.759
So caret is like a unified interface of models, and that was written in like 2005, I think.

00:03:41.759 --> 00:03:45.160
But that's like 2005 code.

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:49.119
And that works pretty well, but there's some, it's definitely not tidy, right?

00:03:49.119 --> 00:03:50.960
It's like the most untidy package.

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:55.979
And so what I wanted to do is sort of reimplement this sort of like model interface, knowing

00:03:55.979 --> 00:04:00.559
all the things that I know now after implementing it for like 250 like models.

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:05.000
So parsnip is sort of that part of caret where we're looking at like a unified interface

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:10.240
that's really consistent with a tidyverse and does some things differently that I've

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:12.479
learned to appreciate over time.

00:04:12.479 --> 00:04:13.479
All right.

00:04:13.479 --> 00:04:17.959
So one thing we do in parsnip is, you know, it's this unified interface, but we decided

00:04:17.959 --> 00:04:21.140
to organize the models a little bit differently than before.

00:04:21.140 --> 00:04:25.119
So what we do is we say, you know, what kind of model, generally speaking, are you trying

00:04:25.119 --> 00:04:26.119
to fit?

00:04:26.119 --> 00:04:30.559
So are you trying to fit like a King or Snapper model or random forest or logistic regression

00:04:30.559 --> 00:04:32.760
or let's say linear regression, right?

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:37.559
So let's define what the type of model is as opposed to using LM or Glenet or what have

00:04:37.559 --> 00:04:38.559
you.

00:04:38.559 --> 00:04:42.799
So once we have a specification for the model, what we can do is we can then generalize how

00:04:42.799 --> 00:04:43.799
to fit them, right?

00:04:43.799 --> 00:04:48.839
So if I say, and this is on the next slide, I think, if I say I'm going to fit a linear

00:04:48.839 --> 00:04:51.640
regression, that usually means like slopes and intercepts, right?

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:54.279
And there are a variety of different ways you can estimate that.

00:04:54.279 --> 00:04:58.359
So in parsnip, what we do is we sort of organize all these models and their interfaces by what

00:04:58.359 --> 00:05:02.720
you're trying to do as opposed to the way you would try to do it.

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:07.440
It has a tidy interface, so it's really consistent with the pipe and all the other tiny model

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:09.600
packages that we have.

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:15.040
It also, and this is a really big deal, very much like broom, we spend a lot of time defining

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:18.059
what we think a predictable interface would be.

00:05:18.059 --> 00:05:21.839
Predictable in the sense that like, okay, if I do predictions on an object, do I know

00:05:21.839 --> 00:05:24.359
what I'm going to get before I get it?

00:05:24.359 --> 00:05:27.000
In many packages, you don't know that.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:32.239
So we spend a lot of time trying to come up with like a convention or a guideline publicly.

00:05:32.239 --> 00:05:36.679
So we publish all this stuff and want feedback as to like what those return values should

00:05:36.679 --> 00:05:39.440
look like if you're going to get them.

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:43.239
So if you want to, you can follow, I'm not going to click on it, but you can follow this

00:05:43.239 --> 00:05:47.040
modeling package guideline, which, you know, we started right, and some of it's specific

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:52.559
to tidyverse stuff and other parts of it are specific to just general modeling ideas.

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:56.920
And you can see what we, our decisions were there, but, you know, it's not like completely

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:57.920
written in stone.

00:05:57.920 --> 00:06:01.160
So if you do have opinions, we'd love to hear them so you can file a get issue and we can

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:04.119
discuss them.

00:06:04.119 --> 00:06:08.760
There's one post about parsnip on the tidyverse blog.

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:12.380
We have another one sort of queued up after the conference that's more about the inner

00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:18.720
workings of parsnip and how it does what it does the way it does it.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:24.279
So you know, one thing about ggplot2 and recipes is they kind of defer evaluation of things.

00:06:24.279 --> 00:06:29.040
So for example, like if you create your ggplot code and then if you don't assign that ggplot

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:32.920
to an object and you hit enter, what you're doing is you're invoking whether you know

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:37.200
it or not, like the print function on that object.

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:41.480
So ggplot actually doesn't do anything really until you explicitly like print it, whether

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:46.000
you use the print command, like you save it to like an object and do print, that's when

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.239
all the stuff happens with ggplot, so it's drawing stuff and doing stuff, right?

00:06:50.239 --> 00:06:54.679
And the same thing with recipes is you define a recipe, but you don't really do anything

00:06:54.679 --> 00:06:57.920
until you need to prepare or use the recipe, right?

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:01.480
So once we start deferring the evaluation of what we want to do, it opens up a lot of

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:06.359
doors to make maybe the workflow a little more sensible.

00:07:06.359 --> 00:07:10.559
So the way, so let's say you have some data, let's say you have, I don't know, some data

00:07:10.559 --> 00:07:18.119
on cars and maybe they're miles per gallon and maybe there's like, I don't know, let's

00:07:18.119 --> 00:07:21.619
just say 32 data points in the data set.

00:07:21.619 --> 00:07:27.119
So you know, as an example, hypothetical example, so we have like a meta package called tiny

00:07:27.119 --> 00:07:30.720
models and you can load that and you'll get dplyr and ggplot and parsnip and some other

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:31.720
stuff.

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:35.239
So you know, what we could do is let's say we want to fit a penalized regression model,

00:07:35.239 --> 00:07:39.040
like ridge regression, you know, if you're used to neural nets, this is like a weight

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:43.679
decay model, but we use like a L2 penalty for the statisticians in the audience, you

00:07:43.679 --> 00:07:48.239
know, and what we'll say is we want to fit a linear regression and then we have a little

00:07:48.239 --> 00:07:53.279
bit of details about the specifics of that, and let's say we kind of know what the penalty

00:07:53.279 --> 00:07:57.000
should be, like really, you know, fairly low value of like .01.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:02.399
So what we can do is we can find a specification for that model using this linear underbar

00:08:02.399 --> 00:08:06.600
reg and say the penalty should be this, and if we print it out, you know, it doesn't really

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:10.760
have much detail because we haven't specified much detail, and a lot of times the detail

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:14.160
comes in terms of like how are we going to fit this regression.

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:20.920
So at least in parsnip, I mean, as we speak, we could fit that using LM or Glimnet or Spark

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:24.920
or Stan or Keras, right, and that's just the ones we've implemented.

00:08:24.920 --> 00:08:29.839
So what we did is we kind of decoupled, you know, the estimation procedure and the package

00:08:29.839 --> 00:08:35.559
that you use to accomplish that from the actual specification of the model, all right?

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:41.520
So you'll see, for example, if you want to use Glimnet, we can pipe in what we call the

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:46.320
computational engine, and again, the computational engine is sort of a mashing together of the

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:51.200
type of estimator, like is it least squares or is it using Bayes method or is it using

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:56.640
like, you know, Keras, with the model package that we would probably use, okay?

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:03.000
So, you know, the engine might be like LM or Glimnet or Keras or Stan and that kind of thing.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:07.000
And also one other thing about the engines is they don't have to be in R, right?

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.640
I mean, with Reticulate and all this other stuff, you know, we know how to like form

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:15.159
and R's always been really good at this, form out the computations to a different language

00:09:15.159 --> 00:09:17.039
or platform or something like that.

00:09:17.119 --> 00:09:21.320
So again, if we're not doing like immediate execution of these things, it allows us to

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:26.960
set up all the things we need to do to get more general results back.

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:30.479
So let's say we start with that regression model specification and we say we want to

00:09:30.479 --> 00:09:34.359
fit Glimnet, you don't really ever need to use this function, but I wrote this function

00:09:34.359 --> 00:09:38.719
called translate and what that does is say, well, okay, you said you wanted to fit this

00:09:38.719 --> 00:09:42.239
kind of model and now that you're saying you want to use it with Glimnet, like how would

00:09:42.239 --> 00:09:43.239
that actually work?

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:47.679
And what translate does is it prints out like a template or a shell of what that code would

00:09:47.679 --> 00:09:48.679
look like.

00:09:48.679 --> 00:09:52.440
So if you look down here, you can see, okay, we're using the Glimnet function, Glimnet

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:57.640
package, we don't know what X and Y are and I should also say that Glimnet only has X

00:09:57.640 --> 00:09:58.640
and Y.

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:02.640
So if your data has dummy variables or, you know, you start off with a data frame, then

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:06.520
you've got to do the work of, you know, creating your indicator variables, converting it to

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:10.359
a matrix and all that stuff to get Glimnet to work.

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:14.760
So the underlying code would use that X, Y interface for Glimnet, lambda is the penalty

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:21.000
function for that particular function and then, you know, since we know we're doing

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.239
linear regression, it automatically sets the family to regression, right?

00:10:24.239 --> 00:10:29.159
So this is like the template of what it's going to use for code when it translates the

00:10:29.159 --> 00:10:36.719
model specification to the underlying engine code that's going to be used.

00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:41.000
And, you know, we don't, you know, especially for Glimnet, we don't usually need the data

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.080
to make that specification, right?

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:46.119
So up to now, I haven't used any data, right?

00:10:46.119 --> 00:10:49.520
This could be on empty cars, it could be on, let's see, there's only two data sets, there's

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:51.559
empty cars and Boston housing.

00:10:51.559 --> 00:10:52.559
Right.

00:10:52.559 --> 00:10:58.679
So, right, so, you know, at this point, I haven't said anything about the data and I'll

00:10:58.679 --> 00:11:03.320
show you a counterexample of that in a minute, but once we have our data, we can actually

00:11:03.320 --> 00:11:05.679
fit a model to this specification.

00:11:05.679 --> 00:11:10.840
And so you can use the fit function to, you know, you give it a formula and the data set

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:15.039
and it goes out and fits your Glimnet model, or if you do want to use the formula method

00:11:15.039 --> 00:11:19.280
because that's more convenient for you, even though Glimnet doesn't have that, you know,

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:22.159
Parsnip will do the same thing that Carrot and other people do is they say, okay, we'll

00:11:22.159 --> 00:11:26.919
do that work to generate all the dummy variables and track all that stuff that we need to and

00:11:26.919 --> 00:11:31.359
keep those preprocessing objects and then it will fit the actual Glimnet model and have

00:11:31.359 --> 00:11:36.000
everything it needs encapsulated into that Parsnip object to make predictions and stuff

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:37.000
in the future.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:38.000
Right.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.799
So you can use fit for the formula method and then fit X, Y if you just want to give

00:11:41.799 --> 00:11:42.799
it X and Y.

00:11:42.799 --> 00:11:47.559
All right.

00:11:47.559 --> 00:11:52.239
So when we do prediction, for example, I shouldn't dog Glimnet too much, but, I mean, it is very

00:11:52.239 --> 00:11:56.520
frustrating that you get very different data types under different situations.

00:11:56.520 --> 00:11:59.479
So if you're just working with like one data set, you might not notice this, but if you

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:03.719
do any programming with Glimnet, there's like a ton of like if then statements, like, you

00:12:03.719 --> 00:12:07.280
know, if the number of levels my outcome is three, then I have to do this versus one,

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:08.280
I do that.

00:12:08.280 --> 00:12:16.039
And so what we have is this, you know, this idea that you ought to get a very formally

00:12:16.039 --> 00:12:19.679
defined output back when you make predictions.

00:12:19.679 --> 00:12:22.520
And so for regression, at least our first approach to that is to kind of follow what

00:12:22.520 --> 00:12:26.520
Broom did, is you're going to get a table back and that table is always going to have

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:29.880
the same number of rows as the input data set.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:33.080
And I'll show you an example of why that matters in a minute.

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:37.359
But in that table, in that table for regression, the value or the column name you're always

00:12:37.359 --> 00:12:40.039
going to get is going to be called dot pred, right?

00:12:40.039 --> 00:12:44.479
No matter what model you use that, you know, how the model works, whatnot, you're always

00:12:44.479 --> 00:12:50.200
going to get a table for regression with one column of dot pred.

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:54.239
So in this case, I'm fitting the model to the first 29 rows and predicting the last

00:12:54.239 --> 00:12:55.239
three.

00:12:55.239 --> 00:12:56.919
And I'm going to get three rows back.

00:12:56.919 --> 00:12:59.440
So why would I make a big deal out of this?

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:04.280
Well, with a lot of like common R prediction functions, what they do is they use NA dot

00:13:04.280 --> 00:13:07.320
omit either explicitly or silently.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:12.239
And so, you know, if I have 100 data points and three of those rows have missing values

00:13:12.239 --> 00:13:15.320
and I make a prediction, I get 97 rows back.

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:18.919
And then I'm like, whoa, like now I got to figure out where the missing three rows are.

00:13:18.919 --> 00:13:23.479
If I want to merge that into a data set, you know, I got to do some extra work to get there.

00:13:23.479 --> 00:13:27.400
And so, you know, we became very, very frustrated with that and this idea that you return the

00:13:27.400 --> 00:13:31.039
number of rows that you started out with.

00:13:31.039 --> 00:13:36.599
If I induce a missing value in the first data point and fit the same model and do the prediction,

00:13:36.599 --> 00:13:38.400
I always get an NA back.

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:39.400
Okay.

00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:43.679
So you can always just like bind columns to your data frame and not have to worry about

00:13:43.679 --> 00:13:46.440
is it going to match up or not.

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:50.960
Now one other thing about Glimnet, which is really awesome, is Glimnet has this penalty

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:56.200
parameter and I specified it here and that's kind of unusual thing to do with Glimnet.

00:13:56.200 --> 00:14:03.039
One really cool aspect of this particular model is it can fit using like one model fit,

00:14:03.039 --> 00:14:07.900
it can get the entire path or entire spectrum of lambda values.

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:12.239
So all the lambda values for that model are kind of encapsulated into that Glimnet object.

00:14:12.239 --> 00:14:15.599
So when I get predictions for Glimnet, I can say, well, give me this lambda or that lambda

00:14:15.599 --> 00:14:17.719
or this other one and fit it over and over again.

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:23.479
But the smarter thing would be to not specify lambda and basically get the Glimnet object

00:14:23.479 --> 00:14:25.479
that can predict any lambda at once.

00:14:25.479 --> 00:14:26.479
Okay.

00:14:26.479 --> 00:14:28.679
And that's a really cool aspect of that model.

00:14:28.679 --> 00:14:34.239
The problem with doing that with this package, though, is it gives you like a bunch of labeled

00:14:34.239 --> 00:14:39.000
columns and you have to kind of trust that the lambda values, the penalty values that

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.919
you're predicting at correspond to those.

00:14:41.919 --> 00:14:45.400
And so, you know, the first time I looked at this, it doesn't say anywhere that they're

00:14:45.440 --> 00:14:48.280
going to go in increasing order or decreasing order.

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:52.679
So it's a little bit scary to use if you first start using it.

00:14:52.679 --> 00:14:57.840
So since Glimnet can return for the same row multiple predictions at different lambdas,

00:14:57.840 --> 00:15:01.200
what do we do with this, like, you know, I start with an input of three rows and I come

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:03.640
out with an input, you know, an output of three rows.

00:15:03.640 --> 00:15:06.440
How are we going to take care of that?

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:09.059
So what we do is we basically produce a list column.

00:15:09.059 --> 00:15:12.599
So in this case, there's 80 possible values of lambda that it fit.

00:15:12.599 --> 00:15:16.559
And when I make the prediction, instead of using the predict method, because not all

00:15:16.559 --> 00:15:21.640
models have this feature, we use another function called multi-predict.

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:26.640
And there's a silent lambda value or argument here for Glimnet, and it by default uses all

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:27.640
the lambdas.

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:31.840
And so what that does is in this particular instance, there's 80 possible lambdas.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:37.359
So what you get is you get a table back for each row, and that table has two columns and

00:15:37.359 --> 00:15:38.359
80 rows.

00:15:38.679 --> 00:15:45.280
And so if I look at the first row of that data set, that table, and remember the holdout

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:49.719
object here had its first value had a missing data point in it, and so what it does is it

00:15:49.719 --> 00:15:54.640
basically gives you a table with 80 missing values for the dot pred and then all the corresponding

00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:59.000
lambdas that you would have gotten predictions for if you hadn't had missing data.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.640
Maybe more informative is to look at the second one, and then you can see if we look at that

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:06.440
particular table, the first five rows of it, you know, we have our predicted values across

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:08.039
all the lambdas.

00:16:08.039 --> 00:16:11.359
And so you might say, well, like, jeez, you know, I can't ggplot that.

00:16:11.359 --> 00:16:14.940
So the good news is, like, you know, unnest and tidy R will just, you know, simply just

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:16.799
make that happen for you.

00:16:16.799 --> 00:16:18.239
So that's like a nice little feature.

00:16:18.239 --> 00:16:21.940
So what we want to do is we want to have these, like, defined standards.

00:16:21.940 --> 00:16:25.599
So another good example is if you're doing, like, quantile regression, you might want

00:16:25.599 --> 00:16:30.140
to get predictions on, like, I don't know, like 10 or 15 or 100 different quantiles.

00:16:30.140 --> 00:16:34.799
So rather than you having to program your way around that, now you get back a table

00:16:34.799 --> 00:16:39.119
with those values in it, and you don't have to worry about doing special things for quantile

00:16:39.119 --> 00:16:45.080
regression versus something else.

00:16:45.080 --> 00:16:47.919
One last thing I'll talk about is this idea of data descriptors.

00:16:47.919 --> 00:16:51.559
So if you think about, like, random forest, which a lot of people have seen, random forest,

00:16:51.559 --> 00:16:53.640
the main tuning parameter is something called mtry.

00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:59.039
And when random forest goes to build a tree, mtry is the number of randomly selected predictors

00:16:59.039 --> 00:17:01.880
it will choose as candidates for that split.

00:17:01.880 --> 00:17:06.800
So if you say mtry equals 3, and you have 100 predictors, it will choose a random 3

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:10.599
out of that 100 as candidate variables to split on.

00:17:10.599 --> 00:17:13.160
And then it gets the next split and chooses another 3.

00:17:13.160 --> 00:17:16.000
And there's good reason, it sounds like a weird thing to do, but there's a very good

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:20.239
reason that they do that, and it actually has a big effect upon performance.

00:17:20.239 --> 00:17:23.319
So when I said, like, we usually don't need the data to specify a model, that's really

00:17:23.319 --> 00:17:27.599
not true for a random forest, because mtry is related to the number of columns in the

00:17:27.599 --> 00:17:28.599
data set.

00:17:28.599 --> 00:17:33.040
So we were starting to think about, like, geez, how would you write a specification

00:17:33.040 --> 00:17:38.239
that does involve the data, but you need something to use the characteristics of the data?

00:17:38.239 --> 00:17:39.920
So we have this thing called data descriptors.

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:45.680
We have these, like, you can see them listed here, these little functions that can capture

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:48.760
different aspects of the data, if not the data themselves.

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:54.739
So if I want to know how many predictors I have, we have a little data descriptor function

00:17:54.739 --> 00:17:59.140
that will calculate that before and after any dummy variables are created.

00:17:59.140 --> 00:18:04.219
So what you can do is you can use these little functions in the model specification.

00:18:04.219 --> 00:18:09.660
So let's say I want to fit a random forest model, and I want to use 75% of the predictors,

00:18:09.660 --> 00:18:13.199
whether I have 10 predictors or 1,000 predictors or whatnot.

00:18:13.199 --> 00:18:16.979
What you can do is you can start the specification for random forest, tell it, you know, let's

00:18:16.979 --> 00:18:22.140
say you want to tell it how many trees to use, and then you can say, well, give me the

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:26.939
number of predictors before dummy variables, you know, find 75% of those, and make sure

00:18:26.939 --> 00:18:29.219
I get an integer by using floor here.

00:18:29.219 --> 00:18:32.979
Now when you run this, like when you run this model specification, of course there's no

00:18:32.979 --> 00:18:34.260
data here, right?

00:18:34.260 --> 00:18:37.979
So what it does is it just saves that expression, and whether you're fitting this model on the

00:18:37.979 --> 00:18:41.739
entire training set or you're resampling with, let's say, cross-validation would be about

00:18:41.739 --> 00:18:46.020
90% of your training set, it does this calculation every time, all right?

00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:49.859
So if we use translate here, what you see is, the first thing you see is random forest

00:18:49.859 --> 00:18:54.300
substituted instead of trees, the thing you would have had to remember for the random

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:58.939
forest package is entry, and then you still see this expression here that has not been

00:18:58.939 --> 00:19:01.020
evaluated yet, okay?

00:19:01.020 --> 00:19:07.380
So when I go to evaluate that using my data, you get a value of 7, so it runs only at that

00:19:07.380 --> 00:19:12.219
point and substitutes the value in there for the data that you're actually using when you

00:19:12.219 --> 00:19:18.180
invoke the fit command, and you can see, you know, we have one column for the number of

00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:22.420
outcomes, and then you can see that we actually get the right value here.

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:25.339
So there's a ton more to talk about with Portsnet, but, you know, I'm going to get the stink eye

00:19:25.339 --> 00:19:31.619
from Davis if I keep talking, so, you know, just a quick look at the things we're thinking

00:19:31.619 --> 00:19:32.619
about.

00:19:32.619 --> 00:19:36.619
We want to think about how we're talking about models, right?

00:19:36.619 --> 00:19:41.380
So sometimes how we talk about models is related to the way the data is structured.

00:19:41.380 --> 00:19:45.219
So you know, I used to do a lot of work where I had repeated measures on a particular experimental

00:19:45.219 --> 00:19:46.219
unit.

00:19:46.219 --> 00:19:49.780
So like if you have a database with your customers in them, you might have multiple rows over

00:19:49.780 --> 00:19:53.260
time for your customers, or if you're in a clinical trial, you might follow patients

00:19:53.260 --> 00:19:54.260
over time.

00:19:54.260 --> 00:19:58.140
So if you have like a really simple repeated measure experiment where you have a single

00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:03.260
sort of like clustering effect or random effect, like patient or customer, you might want to

00:20:03.260 --> 00:20:05.780
fit some sort of model, excuse me.

00:20:05.780 --> 00:20:09.339
You might fit that using a random intercept model, or you might use like a hierarchical

00:20:09.339 --> 00:20:14.180
Bayesian model, or you might fit that using like a correlated error model, like GE.

00:20:14.180 --> 00:20:16.859
So what we could do is we could have the different engines reflect something about

00:20:16.859 --> 00:20:19.859
the model and the experimental design for that model.

00:20:19.859 --> 00:20:23.739
And so you can try all these different things, and they kind of in some ways estimate models

00:20:23.739 --> 00:20:31.140
are either identical, functionally like identical, or extremely similar in spirit.

00:20:31.140 --> 00:20:32.140
And so try different things.

00:20:32.140 --> 00:20:34.260
So it doesn't have to be like random forest models.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:39.579
Sometimes we can, you know, confound that with the type of data that we're using, okay?

00:20:39.579 --> 00:20:40.579
So thanks a lot.

00:20:40.579 --> 00:20:41.579
Appreciate you coming.

00:20:41.579 --> 00:20:49.619
Thank you.

00:20:49.619 --> 00:20:57.979
Think we have time for one question.

00:20:57.979 --> 00:21:03.420
Hi.

00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:08.180
Thank you for this, you know, really, really exciting and very useful development.

00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:10.239
It's really great to see it.

00:21:10.239 --> 00:21:12.040
I'd really like to use it in production.

00:21:12.040 --> 00:21:16.880
Now, in November, we have 0.01 of PartsNip on C-Run.

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:21.680
Would you recommend that we actually go towards the customer with models built on there, or

00:21:21.680 --> 00:21:24.680
how long do we have to wait?

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:26.680
That's kind of a tough question to answer.

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:29.079
Three, four years tops.

00:21:29.079 --> 00:21:30.520
Five.

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:31.520
No more than five.

00:21:31.520 --> 00:21:34.239
No, I mean, so, okay, yeah, this is a good question.

00:21:34.239 --> 00:21:36.239
I mean, it's the first version.

00:21:36.239 --> 00:21:39.359
We want to see what people think and what things people encounter.

00:21:39.359 --> 00:21:40.359
It's been out for a few months.

00:21:40.359 --> 00:21:43.359
We've had almost no GitHub issues, which hopefully means people are using it.

00:21:43.359 --> 00:21:45.199
They're not finding any.

00:21:45.199 --> 00:21:50.280
But the main thing I would say about that is PartsNip in our sample and a lot of other

00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:54.880
things are pieces of a wider puzzle, and, you know, two or three of those things are

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:57.160
not exist yet.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:02.439
So for example, like I have here, we want to integrate PartsNip with recipes and things

00:22:02.439 --> 00:22:03.439
like that.

00:22:03.439 --> 00:22:05.640
So we're going to have, I don't know if it's going to be called a pipeline, but we're going

00:22:05.640 --> 00:22:09.479
to have like a pipeline object that then you can use fit on that.

00:22:09.479 --> 00:22:11.880
So I wouldn't say that, like, PartsNip's not ready for prime time.

00:22:11.880 --> 00:22:15.319
I'd just say that, well, you can use it, but you'd still be lacking a lot of things that

00:22:15.319 --> 00:22:16.839
you would get otherwise.

00:22:16.839 --> 00:22:21.920
So I'm hoping by the end of this time next year, let's say, that if you were to ask that

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:23.520
question, I'd say, yeah, we're good.

00:22:23.520 --> 00:22:29.680
So in my brain, that's what I anticipate the timeline would suggest, but that's what I

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:30.680
think.

